ACT II. SCENE VI.

Pamphilus is ordered in by his father: and Byrrhia, having learned all· he wanted to know goes to acquaint· his master with it. Davus and Simo are, therefore, left to themselves. The former plays upon the latter with great cunning ς and whilst Simo is in doubtwhat to think, the other artfully combats his suspicions, by which the plot is advanced. As each distrusted the other, and it was the interest of both to disguise their real sentiments as much as possible, this gives rise to a very artful conversation, where the poet has succeeded ver-y happily in making both speak agreeably to their characters
